related_questions.question: Is Alaska wild rhubarb edible?
related_questions.snippet: The entire plant is edible. If consuming the stalk, it's advised to strip the outer skin off. One cup of wild rhubarb contains 10% of recommended daily fiber, 44% of vitamin C, 20% calcium, and 72% vitamin A.
related_questions.title: Wild Rhubarb - Alaska Guide

related_questions.question: Can humans eat wild rhubarb?
related_questions.snippet: Botanically known as Rumex Crispus, it's also called Wild, Rhubarb, Yellow Dock, Sour Dock, and Coffee Weed. Curly Dock is native to Africa and Eurasia. It's primarily used in culinary applications, as its leaves, stalks, and seeds are all edible when adequately cleaned.

related_questions.question: Is there rhubarb in Alaska?
related_questions.snippet: Incidentally, one nickname for rhubarb is “pie plant.” Once established, rhubarb generally thrives with little attention in many Alaska locations. It is even thriving and volunteering on the edge of the trees in my yard with absolutely no care. Not only is it prolific, the harvest period is also quite lengthy.
related_questions.title: More Ways to Use Rhubarb - It Grows in Alaska

related_questions.question: Is wild rhubarb the same as regular rhubarb?
related_questions.snippet: Common burdock, also known as "Wild Rhubarb" is a weed that has a similar appearance to garden varieties of rhubarb. Its misleading common name and its similar features has been the reason for much confusion.
